{"id":"7d0147b9-6b7d-4239-a81b-9cf2f2437395","timestamp":"2026-03-05T13:38:42.546Z","file":"output.txt","function":"is","change_type":"bug_fix","description":"Agent-applied fix","diff":{"before":"const fs = require('fs');\nconst path = require('path');\n\n// Load the project map from a JSON file\nfunction loadProjectMap() {\n    const data = fs.readFileSync(path.join(__dirname, 'project_map.json'));\n    return JSON.parse(data);\n}\n\n// Save the project map to a JSON file\nfunction saveProjectMap(projectMap) {\n    fs.writeFileSync(path.join(__dirname, 'project_map.json'), JSON.stringify(projectMap));\n}\n\n// Your existing code...\nThis is an example of how you can use the `fs` module to read and write files in Node.js. In this case, we're using a synchronous version of `readFileSync` to load the project map from a JSON file named 'project_map.json'. We then parse the data into a JavaScript object with `JSON.parse()`.\n\nSimilarly, we use `writeFileSync` to save the project map back to the same file in a stringified format using `JSON.stringify(projectMap)`. \n\nPlease replace 'your existing code...' with your actual code. This way you can load and save changes without re-reading the files.","after":"Sure, here is how you can implement this using Python and its built-in modules:\n\nimport os\nfrom typing import List\n\ndef write_file(filename: str, content: str) -> None:\n    with open(filename, 'w') as file:\n        file.write(content)\n\ndef read_file(filename: str) -> str:\n    if not os.path.exists(filename):\n        raise FileNotFoundError(\"The specified file does not exist.\")\n    \n    with open(filename, 'r') as file:\n        return file.read()\n\nIn this code, `write_file` function is used to write content into a file and `read_file` function is used to read the content of a file. The functions are generic in nature and can be used for any type of files like text files, CSV files etc. \n\nPlease replace 'filename' with your actual filename and 'content' with the string you want to write into the file. You can also use `read_file` function by replacing 'filename' with your actual filename. The functions will return the content of the file if it exists, otherwise they will raise a FileNotFoundError."},"tags":["txt","bug_fix"],"hash":"145e2ccca2c7c092eb5795ba8876d1c5"}
